    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/9nWI3jtK.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1545009,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1438733,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1438733/cat",
                "reputation": 67612,
                "display_name": "Cat",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1354644283,
            "creation_date": 1354644283,
            "body": "<p>Assuming you are trying to use the smiley face <code>:)<\/code> as a delimiter, there is a consideration you have to make: <code>split()<\/code> accepts regex, so you have to escape (with <code>\\\\<\/code>) any <a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/characters.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">special characters<\/a> you use (including but not limited to <code>()[]+*<\/code>):<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>emoticon=e.split(\":\\\\)\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://ideone.com/Oc8M87\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>Proof-of-concept on IDEOne<\/strong><\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13709131,
            "question_id": 13709101
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9ebd56a00cb20654f2bdbd9240a86f95?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 54976,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 164553,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/164553/brigham",
                "reputation": 14638,
                "display_name": "Brigham",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1354645349,
            "creation_date": 1354644314,
            "body": "<p>Use <code>Pattern.quote<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>emoticon = e.split(Pattern.quote(\":)\"));\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>It will surround your <code>String<\/code> with <code>\\Q<\/code> and <code>\\E<\/code> and escape any <code>\\E<\/code> substrings within your pattern.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 13709140,
            "question_id": 13709101,
            "last_edit_date": 1354645349
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/67a8d125cd7608786d3989741d552083?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 1944253,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1749753,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1749753/jlordo",
                "reputation": 37914,
                "display_name": "jlordo"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1354644286,
            "creation_date": 1354644286,
            "body": "<p>you need to escape the braces:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>emoticon=e.split(\":\\\\)\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>but you know, this will get rid of the emoticon, right?<\/p>\n\n<p>to retrieve it out of some text you'll need something like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; emoticons = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\n// adjust regex to find more emoticons\nPattern pattern = Pattern.compile(\":\\\\)\");\nMatcher matcher = pattern.matcher(input);\nwhile (matcher.find()) {\n    emoticons.add(matcher.group());\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 13709132,
            "question_id": 13709101
        }
    ],
